<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Chandigarh</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Where <em>Order Meets Beauty</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Chandigarh is unlike any other city in India. Born not from centuries of organic growth but from a single act of deliberate creation — it is one of the world's great experiments in planned urban living, a city conceived from scratch after the trauma of Partition split Punjab and left its old capital Lahore on the Pakistani side. Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru commissioned the Swiss-French architect Le Corbusier in 1951 to build a city that would be, in his words, "unfettered by the traditions of the past, a symbol of the nation's faith in the future." Le Corbusier designed Chandigarh as a living organism — the Capitol Complex (Legislature, High Court and Secretariat) as the head, the city centre (Sector 17) as the heart, the industrial areas as the stomach, and the residential sectors as the lungs. Every sector was self-sufficient: a school, a market, a health centre, parks and recreational areas built into each 800m × 1200m block. The result is a city of extraordinary livability — wide tree-lined roads, abundant green space (Chandigarh has 26 parks in the Capitol Complex zone alone), clean air from the Shivalik foothills, and an urban design that still feels futuristic 70 years later. The Capitol Complex is a UNESCO World Heritage Site — one of only 17 modern buildings in the world to receive the designation. Chandigarh is the joint capital of two states: Punjab and Haryana (both carved from the original Punjab). It consistently ranks as India's cleanest and most liveable city — with the highest per capita income, some of India's best schools and hospitals, and a quality of life that draws migrants from across North India. The Rock Garden — a 40-acre sculpture park built entirely from urban waste and recycled industrial materials by Nek Chand, a government roads inspector who worked secretly on it for 18 years — is one of the most extraordinary acts of individual artistic vision in the world.</p>
</section>

