const placesData=[
  {emoji:"🏛️",name:"Capitol Complex",location:"Sector 1 — UNESCO World Heritage Site",desc:"One of only 17 modern buildings in the world designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site — Le Corbusier's Capitol Complex comprises the Punjab & Haryana High Court (1955), the Secretariat (1958) and the Punjab Legislative Assembly (1964). The buildings represent the peak of Le Corbusier's Brutalist style — raw concrete monoliths of extraordinary sculptural power, with deep brise-soleil (sun-breakers) that control light and shade in the fierce Punjab sun. The Open Hand Monument — a 26-metre rotating metal sculpture symbolising giving and receiving — dominates the plaza.",fee:["Free (grounds)","Rs.30 museum entry"]},
  {emoji:"🌸",name:"Rock Garden of Chandigarh",location:"Sector 1 — adjoining Capitol Complex",desc:"One of the most extraordinary acts of individual artistic vision in the world — Nek Chand, a government roads inspector, began secretly constructing a sculpture garden on restricted government land in 1958. For 18 years he worked alone at night, carrying industrial waste — broken ceramics, electrical waste, glass bangles, broken tiles, cycle parts — and creating thousands of humanoid and animal figures in an interconnected fantasy landscape of courtyards, waterfalls and winding paths. When discovered in 1975, instead of demolishing it, the government gave Nek Chand a salary and workers to continue. The 40-acre garden now attracts 5,000 visitors daily.",fee:["Rs.30 Indians","Rs.100 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🌹",name:"Zakir Husain Rose Garden",location:"Sector 16",desc:"Asia's largest rose garden — 30 acres containing over 50,000 rose plants of 1,600 varieties, named after India's third President. The garden is most spectacular from late February to mid-March when the roses bloom simultaneously, covering the entire garden in layers of colour from white to deep crimson. The annual Rose Festival (February-March) brings folk performers, food stalls and hundreds of thousands of visitors. The garden is also home to 32 types of medicinal plants and several rare species of tree.",fee:["Free"]},
  {emoji:"🌊",name:"Sukhna Lake",location:"Northeast Chandigarh — Shivalik foothills",desc:"The artificial reservoir created in 1958 by damming the Sukhna Choe stream at the foot of the Shivalik Hills — Sukhna Lake has become the defining recreational space of Chandigarh's daily life. The 3km promenade around the lake is India's most famous morning walk destination — thousands of residents walk here at dawn in all seasons. The lake hosts rowing and sailing events, boats for hire, and the surrounding hillsides are a wildlife sanctuary where sambar deer, nilgai and leopards roam. The dawn reflection of the Shivalik Hills in the lake is Chandigarh's most beautiful daily sight.",fee:["Free — boating charges apply"]},
  {emoji:"🏛️",name:"Government Museum & Art Gallery",location:"Sector 10",desc:"One of North India's finest museums — the Government Museum and Art Gallery in Chandigarh holds an extraordinary collection of Gandhara sculpture (1st–5th century BC Buddhist art from the northwest), Pahari miniature paintings (the mountain-school style from the Himalayan foothills), contemporary Indian art and a significant collection of works by Amrita Sher-Gil (arguably India's greatest modern painter). The building itself — designed by Le Corbusier's collaborator Pierre Jeanneret — is a fine example of the team's approach to institutional architecture.",fee:["Rs.10 Indians","Rs.100 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🦌",name:"Sukhna Wildlife Sanctuary",location:"Northeast Chandigarh — bordering Shivalik Hills",desc:"The 2,600-hectare wildlife sanctuary bordering Sukhna Lake is one of the most accessible wildlife sanctuaries in India — reachable within 20 minutes from the city centre. The sanctuary shelters sambar, barking deer, nilgai, jungle cat, leopard, porcupine and over 150 bird species including hornbills and migratory waterfowl. The Shivalik Hills visible from the sanctuary's edge create a dramatic natural backdrop. The sanctuary is the green lung of Chandigarh — absorbing pollution and moderating the city's temperature.",fee:["Free entry to sanctuary boundary areas"]},
  {emoji:"🎨",name:"Le Corbusier Centre",location:"Sector 19",desc:"The Le Corbusier Centre houses the archive of documents, drawings, photographs and personal effects related to Le Corbusier's work on Chandigarh — including original blueprints, correspondence with Nehru, and the extraordinary planning documents that shaped the city. The building itself is a fine example of the Corbusian aesthetic adapted to the Indian climate. The centre runs guided tours of the Capitol Complex and provides context for understanding the city's architecture for general visitors.",fee:["Rs.20 entry"]},
  {emoji:"🌿",name:"Terraced Garden & Shanti Kunj",location:"Sector 33 & multiple sectors",desc:"Chandigarh's extraordinary network of sector gardens — each sector has its own dedicated green space — culminates in the Terraced Garden (Sector 33), a stepped landscape of seasonal flowers that changes colour with each season. Shanti Kunj (Sector 16) is a contemplative garden of native plants. The city's Butterfly Park (Sector 26) is India's largest enclosed butterfly garden. Chandigarh has more green space per capita than any other Indian city — a direct result of Le Corbusier's planning vision.",fee:["Free — nominal charges at some specific gardens"]},
];

const artsData=[
  {emoji:"🏗️",name:"Le Corbusier's Architecture — A Living Museum",location:"Throughout Chandigarh",desc:"Chandigarh is simultaneously a functioning city and a living museum of 20th century architecture. Le Corbusier's Brutalist vocabulary — raw concrete, deep brise-soleil, roof gardens, pilotis (columns lifting buildings off the ground), modular human-scale proportions — is everywhere. Pierre Jeanneret (Le Corbusier's cousin) designed hundreds of residential buildings, government offices and institutional structures that give the city its distinctive visual character. The Pierre Jeanneret chairs — now iconic mid-century design objects sold for thousands of dollars globally — were originally designed as everyday furniture for Chandigarh's government offices and can still be seen in use."},
  {emoji:"🎨",name:"Pahari Miniature Painting",location:"Government Museum, Sector 10",desc:"The foothills of the Himalayas that cradle Chandigarh were historically the heartland of Pahari (mountain) miniature painting — one of India's most distinctive fine art traditions. The Kangra, Guler, Basohli and Nurpur schools of miniature painting flourished in the small hill kingdoms of the Shivalik range from the 17th to 19th centuries. The Government Museum holds one of India's finest collections of these jewel-like paintings — depicting the Ramayana, Krishna's life, ragamala music themes — in exquisite detail.",
  },
  {emoji:"🪨",name:"Nek Chand's Outsider Art Legacy",location:"Rock Garden, Sector 1",desc:"Nek Chand (1924-2015) is now recognised as one of the world's most significant outsider artists — his Rock Garden appears in international art history books alongside Antonio Gaudí's Sagrada Família and Ferdinand Cheval's Palais Idéal as an extraordinary example of self-taught visionary art. The 12,000+ sculptures he created from industrial and urban waste — all different, all made by hand, all placed in a landscape of interconnected courtyards and waterfalls — represent a philosophical vision of rebirth and transformation that resonates across cultures."},
  {emoji:"🎭",name:"Tagore Theatre & Performing Arts",location:"Sector 18",desc:"Chandigarh's Tagore Theatre is the cultural performance hub of the city and the twin capitals of Punjab and Haryana — hosting classical music concerts, theatre, dance performances and the annual Chandigarh Sangeet Sammelan (music festival). The city's proximity to the classical music traditions of Punjab (Patiala Gharana, one of India's great Hindustani vocal traditions) and the folk traditions of the Punjab-Haryana border means the live performance calendar is exceptional for a city of its size."},
  {emoji:"📐",name:"Chandigarh Architecture Walk",location:"Sector 1 to Sector 22",desc:"The Chandigarh Architecture Walk — conducted by the Chandigarh Heritage Conservation Committee — takes visitors through the Capitol Complex, the Leisure Valley, Sector 17's urban design and the residential sectors to understand Le Corbusier's planning principles. The walk reveals details invisible to casual visitors: the modular grid based on Le Corbusier's Modulor (a human-scale proportion system), the hierarchy of roads (V1 to V7 from highway to footpath), the relationship between buildings and landscape."},
  {emoji:"🎪",name:"Chandigarh Carnival & Rose Festival",location:"Rose Garden, Sector 16 — February/March",desc:"The annual Rose Festival (February-March) is Chandigarh's biggest cultural event — 3 days when the city's most beautiful garden hosts folk performances from Punjab and Haryana (bhangra, giddha, ragini), flower arrangement competitions, food stalls and a general celebration of spring. The Chandigarh Carnival (October-November) is the city's autumn festival — held at various locations across the city with music, art installations, food and cultural performances. Both events reflect the city's unusually high quality of cultural life for its size."},
];

const traditionsData=[
  {emoji:"🌸",name:"Rose Festival — February/March",location:"Zakir Husain Rose Garden, Sector 16",desc:"Chandigarh's signature annual event — 3 days when Asia's largest rose garden transforms into a cultural festival ground. Punjab and Haryana folk artists perform bhangra, giddha and ragini; flower arrangement competitions draw participants from across North India; food stalls serve the full spectrum of Punjabi cuisine; and the garden itself, with 1,600 varieties of rose at peak bloom simultaneously, creates an overwhelming sensory experience. The Rose Festival has been held annually since 1963 and is the social high point of Chandigarh's year."},
  {emoji:"🥁",name:"Bhangra & Giddha — Punjab's Soul",location:"Throughout the city — festivals and celebrations",desc:"As the capital of Punjab, Chandigarh is the institutional home of bhangra — the vigorously energetic harvest dance of Punjab that has spread across the world through the diaspora. The Panjab University and various cultural academies host bhangra and giddha (the women's counterpart) competitions and performances year-round. The sound of dhol (double-headed drum), the sight of men in colourful kurtas and turbans performing the high-energy moves of bhangra, and the women's graceful giddha are Chandigarh's most distinctive cultural expressions."},
  {emoji:"🏃",name:"Morning Walk Culture — Sukhna Lake",location:"Sukhna Lake Promenade",desc:"The morning walk culture of Chandigarh — thousands of residents walking the 3km promenade around Sukhna Lake at dawn — is one of the most distinctive social traditions of the city. The walk is a democratic institution: civil servants, businessmen, college students, elderly couples, serious runners and casual strollers all share the same promenade. The yoga groups that gather at sunrise, the birdwatchers with binoculars, the retired government officials in matching tracksuits, and the young professionals with earphones create a social portrait of Chandigarh's unique character."},
  {emoji:"🎓",name:"Academic & Professional Culture",location:"Panjab University, PGI, Sectors 14 & 25",desc:"Chandigarh's identity is deeply shaped by its concentration of educational and professional institutions — Panjab University (one of India's oldest and most prestigious universities), PGIMER (one of India's finest medical research institutes), several engineering colleges and law schools, and the High Court that employs a large legal community. The cafe culture of Sector 17, the bookshops of Sector 22, the research seminars at PU — these create a distinctively intellectual atmosphere unusual in a city of 1 million."},
  {emoji:"🪔",name:"Lohri & Baisakhi — Punjabi Seasons",location:"Throughout the city — January & April",desc:"Lohri (January 13) — the winter bonfire festival marking the end of the coldest days — is celebrated with extraordinary energy in Chandigarh, where bonfires are lit in every sector, families and neighbours gather to circle the fire, popcorn and rewri (sesame brittle) are thrown into the flames, and bhangra dancing goes on until midnight. Baisakhi (April 13-14) — the Sikh New Year and harvest festival — is celebrated at the Sector 39 Gurdwara and in public spaces with prayer, bhangra and the magnificent sight of turbaned Sikhs in ceremonial dress."},
  {emoji:"🏆",name:"Sports Culture — Cycling, Cricket & More",location:"Throughout the city",desc:"Chandigarh has produced a disproportionate number of India's elite sportspeople — the city's infrastructure (wide cycling paths, sports complexes, Sukhna Lake rowing facilities, cricket stadiums) and its culture of physical activity have created extraordinary sporting achievement. Milkha Singh — the 'Flying Sikh', India's greatest sprinter — lived in Chandigarh for most of his life. The cycling culture (dedicated cycle tracks in every sector) is unique in India and has been part of Le Corbusier's original planning since 1951."},
