const cuisinesData=[
  {emoji:"🍞",name:"Punjabi Dhaba Culture",location:"Sector 22, Dhaba Row & throughout",desc:"Chandigarh is the city where Punjabi dhaba cuisine reaches its most exalted form — the dhabas of Sector 22 and the famous 'Dhaba Row' serve the definitive versions of makhani dal, paneer butter masala, sarson da saag and makki di roti, aloo paratha with a mountain of white butter, and thick lassi in steel glasses. The dhaba tradition — robust, generous, unapologetically rich — reflects Punjab's agricultural abundance. Chandigarh's own contribution is the 'Chandigarh special lassi' — so thick it stands upright in the glass."},
  {emoji:"🧈",name:"Makki di Roti & Sarson da Saag",location:"Traditional restaurants & homes — winter",desc:"The most iconic Punjabi winter dish — mustard greens (sarson) slow-cooked for hours with spinach and then finished with pure desi ghee and ginger, served with thick corn flatbread (makki di roti). This is the taste of winter in Chandigarh — the same dish that was eaten by the farmers of the Punjab plains for centuries, now the centrepiece of wedding menus and restaurant flagship dishes. The best version is still found in homes, but Chandigarh's traditional restaurants (Pal Dhaba, Sindhi Sweets) come close."},
  {emoji:"🍦",name:"Sector 22 Market — Street Food Capital",location:"Sector 22 Market",desc:"Sector 22 Market is Chandigarh's street food capital — the lanes around the market contain decades-old shops serving the city's favourite snacks. Sindhi Sweets (since 1954) for jalebis, gulab jamun and the extraordinary barfi; the gol gappa walas for the city's finest pani puri; Gopal's for chole bhature; the aloo tikki carts serving the Chandigarh version (drier, crispier, with a distinctive tamarind sauce). The market food culture is democratic and multigenerational — the same shops have served the same families for 60-70 years."},
  {emoji:"🧇",name:"Aloo Paratha with White Butter",location:"Sector 22, Sector 15, everywhere",desc:"Aloo paratha — a whole wheat flatbread stuffed with spiced potato, cooked on a flat iron pan with generous ghee, served with a slab of white makhan (unsalted hand-churned butter) and fresh yoghurt — is the Chandigarh breakfast. The city's proximity to Punjab's dairy heartland means the butter and yoghurt are of exceptional quality. The paratha culture of Chandigarh — elaborate stuffings (gobi, mixed vegetable, paneer), the precise technique of rolling without the filling bursting — is a morning institution."},
  {emoji:"🍶",name:"Lassi — The Great Chandigarh Drink",location:"Throughout the city",desc:"Chandigarh lassi — thick, hand-churned yoghurt beaten with a wooden churner, sweetened with sugar and sometimes flavoured with rose water or cardamom, topped with a dollop of malai (cream) — is the city's signature drink. The lassi of Chandigarh is substantially different from the thin yoghurt drinks sold elsewhere — it is almost a meal in itself, so dense that it comes in steel glasses and is eaten partly with a spoon. The lassi stalls of Sector 22 and the famous Balongi Lassi near the city limits serve versions that people drive from other cities to drink."},
  {emoji:"🍲",name:"Dal Makhani — The Chandigarh Night Dish",location:"Restaurants throughout the city",desc:"Dal makhani — whole black urad lentils cooked for 12 hours on a slow fire with butter, cream and tomato — is the most beloved dish of Chandigarh's restaurant culture, served as the centrepiece of dinner. The overnight cooking (the longer the better, some restaurants cook for 24 hours) creates a dish of extraordinary depth and velvet texture. Chandigarh's restaurant version — at Pal Dhaba, at Barbeque Nation, at the five-star Hotel Mountview — is considered among the finest in North India."},
  {emoji:"🎂",name:"Sweets & Bakeries — The Chandigarh Sweet Tooth",location:"Sector 22 & throughout",desc:"Chandigarh has an unusually rich sweet and bakery culture — a legacy of the Partition refugees from Lahore who brought their sweet-making traditions east in 1947. The city's mithai shops (sweet shops) produce gulab jamun, jalebi, barfi, ladoo, pinni (wheat-ghee-sugar sweet eaten in winter) and Chandigarh's own speciality — the 'Chandigarh cake' (a rich dry fruit and ghee preparation). The bakery culture (Chandigarh Baking Company, Sector 22) is also unusually sophisticated for a North Indian city — a legacy of the British administrative tradition."},
];

